text: So this idea of activities, the activities that you do in the present being understood as an investment for the future, this deferral of your present time and the things that you're doing in the present in a kind of cynical way, it's this type of relationship that I'm talking about. And I probably don't, I mean, I have an example of something that happened. And again, it's very familiar, but maybe these examples help. I was at this innovation academy. The innovation academy is this partnership between Trinity and UCD, which is all about trying to get students to be more enterprising and innovative about the knowledge that they use and about how they can orientate it towards industry. But I was at this lecture, not as an attendant. I was serving wine as one of my many part-time jobs as a precarious worker. And there was this other girl there who was an intern at the innovation academy. And she'd been doing this for three months. She had had her master's and she was serving wine. And she told me that it was one of the best jobs she'd done as this intern for this innovation academy and that she'd literally been putting stamps on letters and all the various other menial, pointless tasks you do in internships. But she said, you know, really openly that, you know, the reason she was doing it was, because she'd put it on her CV, you know, and you'd have this innovation academy. And I think that it's that that is surprising. Again, I'm not making a judgment about this person's entirely normal behavior, but it's that type of attitude that you'd have. And internships are possibly the best example of that or the most obvious example of that, of doing something not because you want to do it, not because you see it as having any value. In fact, you recognize it has no value, but you do it because it might be worth it. It might help you get somewhere in the future. There's this deferral. So what I'd argue then is that this kind of absence of future security, this demand that is placed on you to do as much as you can with yourself, rather than kind of liberating you, making you think that you're free to do things, it creates a situation in which you become your own exploiter. You become a self exploiter. You're not mostly exploited at work. You're exploited by yourself. Because you start to think that you can't do enough. You start to think that you don't have enough time to get more qualifications, to be as good as that person beside you. You don't have enough time. You know, you're always squeezing this precious value out of your minutes. And so this irregular work becomes, and the distinction between work and non-work becomes blurred. And this kind of logic of exploitation starts to filter or insinuate through more aspects of your life. The result being that you work harder and you seem to be committing yourself more to work, but you have less security, you have less income. We don't have any more income than we used to. So then the question is, why would you do it? Why do we do it? Why when you think about going back to that film in 1960 and you think about struggles against work, where people resisted this dead time and this alienated time, why is it that now you have a situation that's almost reversed? Where people are actively investing more of themselves into these activities? Well, you know, clearly the causes are because people are delusional. I mean, it's a necessity. It's seen as a necessity. If you don't do these things, you'll be left behind. And that is one of the most important things in this whole situation, I think. It's this myth or this belief that there's going to be a secure or well-paid job at the end of it. This is the carrot that you beat yourself with. And there's a group of people who are doing it. There's a group in London called the Carrot Workers Collective who have taken that image for exactly that reason. So there's this idea that you're told, you know, the sky is the limit and you can be everything. You can be mobile and flexible and creative and responsible and that there's no more barriers to anybody anymore. And there's this motto by Persona, which is the largest temporary agency in Japan. A third of the workforce in Japan are temporary workers. And the motto is, be a regular worker and be exploited for the rest of your life. You know, which is exactly this idea that by being a regular, by not having a fixed job, you're going to be not exploited. You're going to be free. But in reality, that is rarely the case. So just a few statistics. There's more and more well-qualified, well-educated people and there's less and less jobs. In Spain, 40% of graduates work in low-skilled work. Temporary workers who think that they might become regular salaried employees, that only happens for 12% to 15% of temporary workers. That's the number of people who are employed. And in this book, because it's quite a nice example, I think, because it's something that seems, I think, quite familiar. But Guy Standing wrote a book about the precariat in which he tries to describe how this condition of precariousness or precarity can actually help us to identify a new class of people, which I don't really agree with. But he gives this example of a 24-year-old woman who's a social worker. Who earns £28,000 a year and works 37 and a half hours a week. But in reality, she says in an interview, she does work quite a few late nights because some families can't be visited in the daytime. And she also spends more time working on her own and working from home. So she explains, this is a quote. My great frustration is that I've been told for a long while I'm good enough to progress to the next level. And I've taken on tasks beyond my job role. And I've taken on tasks beyond my job role. But there's no recognition of that. I just have to wait until a post becomes available. I think that happens to quite a few people. From the team I started with, I'm the only social worker left. And a lot of them have left due to issues of career support and progression. We do a tough, responsible job. If that was recognised, it might just keep us in the job longer. So here's a situation in which the woman recognises that she's doing work beyond what she's being paid for. In a sense, she's self-exploiting herself. In the hope that she will get this progress. Which is probably unlikely. I don't know, I hope she got a raise. But I want to move on to something else that is related but it's slightly different. And it's about this idea of individual freedom. This idea that you can have it all and that if you just work hard and commit yourself and get educated and network. And apply yourself, that you'll get all these possibilities. Which is true for some people of course. But the flip side of it is this idea of individual responsibility. Which is a far more insidious thing. So I was in the pub the other day and I heard this conversation that was again very familiar. It was these two men and one of them was talking about his son who just left college. And he was saying that his son wasn't working and that he couldn't get a job. And that he was going to go on the dole. So the man's friend said that he'd seen a sign in the local centre that they were hiring people. And he said he was sick of people complaining that there was no jobs because there was jobs. And they both went on to talk about yada yada yada. Young people had to realise that work wasn't fun. And that getting a foot on the ladder was the first step towards getting a job. And it was experience and so on. Really familiar conversation. And it's a conversation that has a really long pedigree. This idea that if people don't have work. They are in work. It must be something that is wrong with them. They must be lazy. Or they mustn't be applying themselves. And it's interesting just because I'm doing some other research on the 18th century. Which was a time in Ireland when people were displaced from the land. And people no longer had a way of supporting themselves through enclosure. And so they became the recipients of kind of meagre charity, poor houses. And they were also left to their own devices. And became kind of vagrants. You know, had to resort to illegal activity. Stealing, poaching, things like that. But all the pamphlets at the time. A lot of the pamphlets. And a popular kind of discourse. Was about how these useless masses were leeching off the wealth of the responsible citizenry. You know, who had worked so hard to get into their positions. And there's something similar about now. Where there's this excess of labour. And an excess of capacities. Basically an excess of people who don't have a function. Within the way that the economy is operating. It's not because they don't want to work. And if they don't want to work in Central. Then that's also okay. But you have this excess. And rather than recognizing that's a problem that is structural. That has to do with an unequal economy. Which isn't about providing employment for people. You see a demonization of people for being scroungers. And for being unproductive. Which is this individualizing of responsibility. And so an important part of that is how. Precarity isn't just something that comes out of the private sector. From free market. From competition. It's something that's being institutionalized in the state. It's something that's being institutionalized through social welfare. So this demand that I've been trying to describe. To work harder on yourself. To upskill. To retrain. Is exactly the discourse that has been used by the state. So you see this shift from welfare. Where people are given money. Or given support. Because they're unable to find work. To work fair. Where increasingly there's conditions. Placed on people who are able to receive that. And that condition reflects people's capacity. To show that they're applying for work. But not only applying for work. But making themselves available for work. By not just sitting at home. But by taking educational courses and things. And so in Ireland you see that with Jobbridge. Which started last year. Which is this internship scheme. Where welfare recipients work for six or nine years. And are paid their regular social welfare rate. Plus an extra 50 euro a month. And this basically takes people. And puts them with businesses. Where they gain valuable experience. Some of them maybe get valuable experience. But there's a website set up. That's quite interesting. Called Scambridge. And basically it was set up. Because there were so many people who had experiences. Of not only the meaninglessness of the internships. And the fact that they didn't help them. Get a foot on the ladder. But also the experience of how it's actually undignified. And not only undignified. What's the word I'm looking for. It's not something that makes people feel better. Which is an argument that is often made by the government. That if you get out of the house. And get into the workplace. And you start to give your confidence and so on. But why would you get confidence. If you were working. And people around you were getting paid a salary. And you were getting paid the crappy dole. And you weren't getting paid. That's not going to make you feel better. Especially if what you're doing with your time. Is putting stamps on letters. And this kind of thing. There's a really funny one that I forget. Last week. Which was about getting valuable experience cleaning. As a cleaning operative. Or something like that. And that the person who left. Would have learned these skills. Had to clean an office or something. Anyway. And yeah. So I shouldn't laugh about this. Because in UK. Where they have something called workfare. Which is a similar scheme to job bridge. But is compulsory in some cases. That people have to take these internships. If they're going to get their welfare. The MP George Osborne said. Young people who do not engage with this offer. Will be considered for mandatory work activity. And those that drop out without good reason. Will lose their benefits. And again. How reminiscent that is of people in the 18th century. And how close that is to the idea of setting up work camps. And things. And I don't want to get too dramatic about it. The idea of considering people for mandatory work. Is quite terrifying. So. I painted a pretty bleak picture I think. And I probably did what I didn't want to do. Which is. To. To. To describe a situation. In which it seems like there's just this reserve army of labour. And we're all being exploited. In our waking hours. And in our sleeping hours. And it's all awful. But clearly it's not that. It's not the case. It's not that totalising. So. While. I think. I think. I think. I think. I think. I think. I think. I think. I think. I think. I think. While. While I think it is the case. That. This uncertainty about the future. And this condition of precarity. Demands that more and more of our. Our time. Not just our work time. But our non-work time. Is taken up. With orientating ourselves. To. To getting work in the future. It's also the case that people. Escape that. Or refuse that. Or find ways of. Of. Not. Entering into that type of. Of logic. We don't all instrumentalise. Things around us. We all don't. We all don't. We all don't. We don't all go to university. And think of as a vehicle to a job. And it's also the case that people aren't. Victims. All the time. They're agents. And so what I wanted to ask. Or yeah. Kind of. Talk about. Just at the conclusion. Is. What then it would mean to refuse work. Today. When these distinctions of work and non-work. Are not so clear. What does it mean. To refuse work. If. Work has extended itself. Into. Many aspects. Of what we do. And we can't. To. Just. Get paid for. The type of work of like. Applying for things. A lot of people. I know. Spend a huge amount of time. Applying for things. Because they have to. Or. Going for interviews. Even. Or. Applying for the dole. Of. Filling out forms. A lot of this time. That is taken up. How do you refuse. That. How do you refuse. That. Demand. To always be so productive. With your time. Which basically. Exhausts you. You know. It exhausts. People. And causes. You know. Mental. Illness problems. As well. The next talk. Is more about that kind of fallout. I think. That. Yeah. I. I. Think. That. Yeah. So. Trying to think about. How you. How you can stop. Having to be so. Productive. All the time. And I think. That part of that. Is. Is. Is about the fear. That people have. Of the future. That they don't have a choice. And. This is what I'm going to. Just maybe. Talk about. As a suggestion. Or talk about. As a. Possibility. Is that a lot of that fear. Is carried by individuals. And this is something. That is also. Characteristic. Of the type of work we do. That even though. It might be social. In some respects. Mostly. It's. Very individualized. And we're very fragmented. So. As individuals. We apply for jobs. On our own. We move between jobs. On our own. We negotiate the dole. On our own. We go for interviews. On our own. We have to face the possibility. We're going to have to move. To another country. On our own. Unless. You know. In a relationship. Or something. You have to build up your CV. On your own. I mean the CV. Is this. Incredibly individualizing. Type of technology. So. In the past. And again. I don't want to idealize it. Too much. But work was something. That had more of an identity. More of a collectivity. Now. The type of work we do. Doesn't have that. And that's part of the reason. Why. We're doing this. Because you're. Kind of relying on yourself. So there's this. So. So. What. What I think is important. Then. Is how you can find ways of. Of overcoming that. Individualized. Experience. And that sense of individual competition. Of competing for resources. And. Competing for. Limited. Job. Places. And the only way. That I can see that happening. Is by. Reclaiming. A kind of. A time. Of. A time. Of. Of. Creating. A time. Together. That. You know. Almost allows you to take a breath. Like a deep breath. It's not this time that. Is so frenetic. And so distracted. And so. Necessarily open. To all these opportunities. But a time. That allows you to stop. A little bit. And to. To be still. For a little bit. With these people. That are there. And. And really. Commit. To what is. Is quite. Is present. You know. Not this idea. Of. A time. It's not. Not something mysterious. But I just think of. For example. This. Building. Superfast. But also lots of these buildings. Superfast was a building where. People. Came together. They. They. They. They. They. Funded it through making meals together. Which is a kind of social. Social activity. But it's also a productive activity. Money was used. To pay for this. Building. That then allowed other people to come there. And. Because people. Using that building. To do. This massive pressure. That basically forces you to get more part time jobs. And essentially take your time away from you. It meant that people could. Could. Could be there in a different way. And it meant that different activities could. Could happen there. It meant that. You could meet. People. That you might not otherwise meet. And in a sense what that is. Is a. A kind of commons. That is created. Between people. And for me that commons. Because it's collective. Allows you to not work so hard. It's as simple as that. Like being. Being. Being. Being. Being. A collective enterprise. And. Being. Being. A collective enterprise. Allows you. To not be so. Bloody. Productive. And industrious. It allows you to. To. To. To. Be lazy. And to. To. To. To like think for no particular reason. And do all these sorts of things. Being non instrumental. And I think that that is. At the crux of this. How you can live more. And work less. And the only way I can see that happening. Is by. People coming together. And being able to. Produce and reproduce their lives. In a very material way. At a distance from. This necessity. To. To. To work so hard. And. I just finished by saying that this. This that I'm saying might seem very simple. But I think what's important about it. Is that it's not. It doesn't have any clear politics to it. And. The reason why. You come together. Is because you. You have this condition. Or we're in this condition of being precarious. It's not because you share. Any. Analysis. It's not because you share any identity. It's not because you share any. Anything. Beyond the fact that. You're. You're. You're people who want to do stuff. And. You need to sustain yourself. And that as a starting point. To hopefully. Maybe. Producing. Ideas. And. And. Extending beyond that. And then producing maybe something like a politics. I think that that that's. An important step. It's a kind of much more immediate. Pragmatic. Concrete. Escape. From a condition of. Precarity. Rather than a resistance. Or a protest. So. That's the. The. So. That's the. That's the end.
